└───────────────────────────┘   └───────────────────────────────────┘
```

### 2.2 Why Strategy Pattern Over Alternatives

| Alternative Approach | Why Rejected |
|---------------------|--------------|
| **Naive `if/else` checks** | Violates Open/Closed Principle; scatters game mode logic across entire codebase; makes testing difficult; creates maintenance burden when adding new modes |
| **Decorator Pattern** | Decorators are better for adding behavior transparently; our strategies have fundamentally different behaviors, not additive enhancements |
| **Template Method** | Requires inheritance hierarchy; less flexible than composition; harder to switch strategies at runtime |
| **State Pattern** | Better for state transitions; our need is behavior selection, not state management |

### 2.3 Supporting Pattern: Factory Pattern

A **Sync Strategy Factory** will be responsible for creating and returning the appropriate strategy based on the current player context (game mode). This cleanly separates:
- **Decision logic** (which strategy to use) - in the factory
- **Execution logic** (how to sync) - in the strategies

